# 🧩 TASK 1: Git & Distributed Version Control

## 📖 Concept Overview

Git is a **distributed version control system (DVCS)** designed to manage source code efficiently across multiple developers.  
Unlike centralized systems, every contributor has a complete copy of the repository, including its full history.

Git works using a **snapshot-based architecture**:
- Each commit represents a snapshot of the entire project.
- Files are identified using SHA-1 hashing.
- This ensures data integrity and tamper detection.

## 🔹 Branching Strategy

- Branches allow parallel development.
- `merge` integrates different development histories.
- `rebase` rewrites commit history to maintain a cleaner linear project structure.

Git’s internal structure is built on:
- Blobs (file content)
- Trees (directories)
- Commits (metadata + snapshots)

